"Seppälä O., Jokela J.","Immune defence under extreme ambient temperature",2011,"Biology Letters","7","1",,"119","122",,,10.1098/rsbl.2010.0459,"http://www.scopus.com/inward/record.url?eid=2-s2.0-79551497696&partnerID=40&md5=c8b8113723cb50a3e9c41b50397c1b6c","EAWAG, Swiss Federal Institute of Aquatic Science and Technology, 8600 Dübendorf, Switzerland; ETH-Zürich, Institute of Integrative Biology, 8092 Zürich, Switzerland","Seppälä, O., EAWAG, Swiss Federal Institute of Aquatic Science and Technology, 8600 Dübendorf, Switzerland, ETH-Zürich, Institute of Integrative Biology, 8092 Zürich, Switzerland; Jokela, J., EAWAG, Swiss Federal Institute of Aquatic Science and Technology, 8600 Dübendorf, Switzerland, ETH-Zürich, Institute of Integrative Biology, 8092 Zürich, Switzerland","Owing to global climate change, the extreme weather conditions are predicted to become more frequent, which is suggested to have an even greater impact on ecological interactions than the gradual increase in average temperatures. Here, we examined whether exposure to high ambient temperature affects immune function of the great pond snail (Lymnaea stagnalis). We quantified the levels of several immune traits from snails maintained in a nonstressful temperature (15°C) and in an extreme temperature (30°C) that occurs in small ponds during hot summers. We found that snails exposed to high temperature had weaker immune defence, which potentially predisposes them to infections. However, while phenoloxidase and antibacterial activity of snail haemolymph were reduced at high temperature, haemocyte concentration was not affected. This suggests that the effect of high temperature on snail susceptibility to infections may vary across different pathogens because different components of invertebrate immune defence have different roles in resistance. This journal is © 2010 The Royal Society.","Immune function; Immunocompetence; Lymnaea stagnalis; Pathogen resistance","antimicrobial activity; climate change; defense behavior; enzyme activity; immune response; infectious disease; pathogenicity; pond; snail; temperature effect; animal; article; greenhouse effect; heat; immunology; Lymnaea; Animals; Global Warming; Hot Temperature; Lymnaea; Gastropoda; Invertebrata; Lymnaea stagnalis",,,,,,"Blanford, S., Thomas, M.B., Pugh, C., Pell, J.K., Temperature checks the Red Queen? Resistance and virulence in a fluctuating environment (2003) Ecology Letters, 6 (1), pp. 2-5. , DOI 10.1046/j.1461-0248.2003.00387.x; Mitchell, S.E., Rogers, E.S., Little, T.J., Read, A.F., Host-parasite and genotype-by-environment interactions: Temperature modifies potential for selection by a sterilizing pathogen (2005) Evolution, 59, pp. 70-80; Walther, G.-R., Post, E., Convey, P., Menzel, A., Parmesan, C., Beebee, T.J.C., Fromentin, J.-M., Bairlein, F., Ecological responses to recent climate change (2002) Nature, 416 (6879), pp. 389-395. , DOI 10.1038/416389a; Karl, T.R., Trenbeth, K.E., Modern global climate change (2003) Science, 302, pp. 1719-1723. , doi:10.1126/science. 1090228; Easterling, D.R., Meehl, G.A., Parmesan, C., Changnon, S.A., Karl, T.R., Mearns, L.O., Climate extremes: Observations, modeling, and impacts (2000) Science, 289, pp. 2068-2074. , doi:10.1126/science.289.5487.2068; Meehl, G.A., Tebaldi, C., More intense, more frequent, and longer lasting heat waves in the 21st century (2004) Science, 305 (5686), pp. 994-997. , DOI 10.1126/science.1098704; Hance, T., Van Baaren, J., Vernon, P., Boivin, G., Impact of extreme temperatures on parasitoids in a climate change perspective (2007) Annu. Rev. Entomol., 52, pp. 107-126. , doi:10.1146/annurev. ento.52.110405.091333; Wegner, K.M., Kalbe, M., Milinski, M., Reusch, T.B.H., Mortality selection during the 2003 European heat wave in three-spined sticklebacks: Effects of parasites and MHC genotype (2008) BMC Evolutionary Biology, 8 (1), p. 124. , DOI 10.1186/1471-2148-8-124; Lindgren, E., Talleklint, L., Polfeldt, T., Impact of climatic ch